lessons.testCode:
You should have a `printMessage` function.

```js
assert.isFunction(printMessage);
```

You should use arrow function syntax.

```js
assert.match(code, /(let|const)\s+printMessage\s*=\s*?\(?.*?\)?\s*=>\s*{\s*[\s\S]*}\s*;?/);
```

Your `printMessage` function should have a parameter called `org`.

```js
assert.match(code, /(let|const)\s+printMessage\s*=\s*?\(?org?\)?\s*=>\s*{\s*[\s\S]*}\s*;?/)

```

Your `printMessage` function should have a console statement.

```js
assert.match(printMessage.toString(),/console\.log\(/);
```

Your console statement should include the template literal `${org} is awesome!`.

```js
assert.match(code, /console\.log\(\s*`[^`]*\${org} is awesome![^`]*`\s*\)/);
```

You should call the `printMessage` function and pass in the string `"freeCodeCamp"`.

```js
assert.match(code,/printMessage\(\s*["']freeCodeCamp["']\s*\)/);
```

Your function call should be below your `printMessage` function definition.

```js
const functionCall = code.indexOf("printMessage(");
const functionDefinition = code.indexOf("printMessage =");

assert.isBelow(functionDefinition, functionCall);
```

Your `printMessage` function call should output `freeCodeCamp is awesome!` to the console. 

```js
const spy = __helpers.spyOn(console, "log");
printGreeting();
assert.sameDeepOrderedMembers(spy.calls, [["Hello there!"]]); 
```

lessons.description:
Just like regular functions, arrow functions can return values. 

Here is an example of an arrow function returning the result of multiplying two numbers:

```js
const multiplyTwoNumbers = (num1, num2) => {
  return num1 * num2;
}

// Output: 12
console.log(multiplyTwoNumbers(3, 4)); 
```

Create a new variable called `addTwoNumbers` and assign it an arrow function. This arrow function should take two parameters called `num1` and `num2`. Inside the body of the function, return the expression of adding `num1` and `num2`.

Below the `addTwoNumbers` function, add a console statement. Inside that console statement, call the `addTwoNumbers` function and pass in the numbers `3` and `4` as arguments.

Open up the console to see the output.

